MESSAGE user "What is the Multi-Point Routing tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Multi-Point Routing tool allows you to place fabrication parts similar to how you create design elements."


MESSAGE user "How do I begin using the Multi-Point Routing tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "First, load the fabrication configuration you want. Then, on the Systems ribbon, click 'Fabrication Part' to open the MEP Fabrication Parts palette."


MESSAGE user "What do I need to do before I can use the Multi-Point Routing tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "You need to specify the service in the MEP Fabrication Parts palette before you can use the tool. Expand the 'Service' drop-down and select a service."


MESSAGE user "How do I activate the Multi-Point Routing tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "After selecting the service, click 'Multi-Point Routing' on the ribbon in the Fabrication panel, or click 'Start Multi-Point Routing' from the MEP Fabrication Parts palette."


MESSAGE user "What happens when the Multi-Point Routing tool is active?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can't use the MEP Fabrication Parts palette to place fabrication parts. You should instead use the Type Selector to pick a straight manufacturing part."


MESSAGE user "How do I route fabrication parts?"
MESSAGE assistant "Click in the drawing area to place your starting point. Then, move your cursor in any direction, and you'll see listening dimensions that help you place parts at the correct length and angle."


MESSAGE user "Can I convert design elements to fabrication parts?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, you can convert a single element, like a duct, pipe, conduit, or cable tray, as well as an entire system to fabrication parts. However, conversion is not possible for all MEP elements."


MESSAGE user "Is there anything important I should know before converting design elements?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, because the design elements are actually converted to fabrication parts in the model, it is best practice to create a copy of the model whenever you plan to convert design content to fabrication parts."


MESSAGE user "How do I convert design elements to fabrication parts?"
MESSAGE assistant "To begin, move the mouse over an element and press TAB to show the chain of elements that are linked to it. Click to select all the highlighted elements."


MESSAGE user "How do I start using MEP fabrication content?"
MESSAGE assistant "The first step is specifying a fabrication configuration. Fabrication parts are created as .itm files, each representing a piece of content with geometrical dimensions and associated data from a manufacturer."


MESSAGE user "What do I need to do to specify a fabrication configuration?"
MESSAGE assistant "To begin, on the Systems ribbon, in the Fabrication panel, click to launch the 'Fabrication Settings' dialogue."


MESSAGE user "How do I load the services I need?"
MESSAGE assistant "Pick out the service you want to use on the Services tab, then click 'Add'.  You can also double-click a service to include it in the loaded list."


MESSAGE user "Can I select multiple services at once?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, you can choose more than one service. Press CTRL or SHIFT and make your choices."


MESSAGE user "Can I add specific parts without adding an entire service?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, on the Parts tab, you can add individual parts without adding the entire service. Expand a folder, navigate to the part you want, select it, and then click 'Add'."


MESSAGE user "How do I finish loading the services and parts?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once you have added the necessary services and parts, click 'OK' to close the Fabrication configuration dialogue."


MESSAGE user "How do I use the loaded services?"
MESSAGE assistant "To use the loaded services, go to the ribbon in the Fabrication panel and click 'Fabrication Part' to open the MEP Fabrication Parts palette."


MESSAGE user "How do I add or remove parts and services?"
MESSAGE assistant "To add or remove parts and services, click 'Reload Configuration'. Keep in mind that you must remove all loaded services before selecting a different configuration."


MESSAGE user "What should I do once I finish making changes to my fabrication settings?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once you're finished, click 'OK' to close the dialogue and save your changes."


MESSAGE user "How do I optimise lengths of ductwork?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can use the Optimise Lengths tool to optimise the length of placed or converted straight parts that do not match standard lengths. First, hover your cursor over a straight fabrication part and press TAB to highlight the chain of connected parts. Then, click to select the highlighted parts."


MESSAGE user "What do I do after selecting the ductwork parts?"
MESSAGE assistant "After selecting the parts, use the Filter tool to deselect the duct fittings from the selection set to ensure that only ductwork lengths are optimised."


MESSAGE user "How do I use the optimise lengths tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "On the contextual ribbon, click Optimise Lengths. This tool will add, remove, or modify the length of straight fabrication parts to maximise the number of standard-length segments as defined in your fabrication configuration."


MESSAGE user "What happens if the tool adds a small segment?"
MESSAGE assistant "If the tool adds a small segment to make up any differences in length, you can select the part and use the Reposition Part control in the drawing area to move it to the other end of the straight run."


MESSAGE user "Can the tool optimise pinned parts?"
MESSAGE assistant "No, straight parts that are pinned or part of a palette will not be optimised by the tool."


MESSAGE user "What does the Optimise Lengths tool do?"
MESSAGE assistant "The tool helps maximise the number of standard-length segments for your ductwork by adding or modifying the lengths of straight segments. It makes it easier to adjust and ensure that the ductwork fits into standard fabrication lengths."



