MESSAGE user "How do I add a new piping material and schedule type?" 
MESSAGE assistant "In the Mechanical Settings, go to Pipe Settings > Segments and Sizes. Create a new material by selecting carbon steel from the materials library, then enter a new schedule description and adjust the size catalogue as needed."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust fluid properties for a piping system?" 
MESSAGE assistant "In the Mechanical Settings dialogue, go to the Fluids section to review, add, or delete fluids. Each fluid has a range of temperatures, viscosities, and densities that affect pipe sizing calculations."


MESSAGE user "Where can I set fluid and temperature for a pipe system?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select a pipe in your model, go to its Type Properties, and set the appropriate fluid and temperature under the Mechanical Flow area."


MESSAGE user "How do I create custom pipe slopes for sloped piping systems?" 
MESSAGE assistant "In the Mechanical Settings dialogue under Pipe Settings, use the Pipe Slopes section to create or delete slopes. For example, you can add a new slope value like 1 inch."


MESSAGE user "What does enabling analysis of closed-loop piping networks do?" 
MESSAGE assistant "In the Mechanical Settings dialogue under Pipe Settings, enable the option in the Calculation area to analyse closed-loop piping networks. This affects how Revit treats such networks during analysis."


MESSAGE user "How do I connect radiators using physical connections?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Use standard modelling tools to manually connect supply and return pipes to radiators. Pay attention to pipe size, elevation, and coordination with other pipes and fittings."


MESSAGE user "What are analytical connections in piping systems?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Analytical connections provide a quick way to connect equipment without routing physical pipes. They still provide system information like flow rate, pressure drop, and velocity."


MESSAGE user "How do I create an analytical connection for a radiator?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Select the heating flow pipe, then click on 'Analytical Connections' in the ribbon and select the radiator. The connection will be displayed as a single line."


MESSAGE user "Can I use analytical connections with pipe sizing tools?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, analytical connections are compatible with Revit's pipe sizing tools. They provide relevant engineering data used for validating design decisions."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new duct system type and assign a system abbreviation?"
MESSAGE assistant "First, select the duct and review its properties. Notice the default system type and absence of a system abbreviation. From the dropdown menu, change the system type (for example, to 'Kitchen Extract') to automatically assign a system abbreviation, default system name, and a system colour."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new piping system?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, right-click on 'Hydraulic Supply' under piping systems, duplicate it, and rename it. Right-click the new system, select 'Type Properties', and adjust the colour and material in the graphics override. Set fluid type to 'water' and temperature to 60°C. Lastly, set the system abbreviation to match the chilled water system."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new pipe type and define routing preferences?"
MESSAGE assistant "Duplicate the standard pipe type and rename it (e.g., 'Low Temperature Hot Water'). Right-click it and choose 'Type Properties', then edit 'Routing Preferences'. Set the pipe segment to 'Carbon Steel Schedule 40', adjust minimum and maximum pipe sizes, and load the appropriate fitting families (threaded fittings for smaller sizes, flanged fittings for larger). Assign fittings and set size ranges accordingly."


MESSAGE user "What’s the process of adding threaded and flanged fittings to a pipe type?"
MESSAGE assistant "Load threaded fittings like caps, elbows, tees, etc., and assign them to pipe sizes up to 3 inches. For sizes above 3 inches, load flanged fittings and assign them in the routing preferences. Adjust minimum and maximum size settings to apply the correct fitting based on pipe diameter."


MESSAGE user "How can I verify that my pipe fittings are correctly applied by size?"
MESSAGE assistant "In a floor plan view set to fine detail level, select the Pipe tool, choose your new pipe type, and set the system type (e.g., hydraulic supply). Draw one section of pipe below 3 inches and another above 3.5 inches. Review fittings to confirm threaded fittings are used on smaller pipes and flanged fittings on larger ones."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a duct colour fill legend to visualise system properties?"
MESSAGE assistant "Duplicate your HVAC floor plan view, rename it appropriately (e.g., 'Duct Velocity'), and place a colour fill legend from the ribbon. Change the colour scheme to 'Duct Velocity'. The colour fill dynamically updates as you modify flow rates or duct sizes, helping highlight areas of concern."


MESSAGE user "How can I simplify the display of duct colour fill legends?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the legend, choose 'Edit Scheme', and change the display option from 'By Value' to 'By Range'. Adjust the range thresholds (e.g., set the minimum to 800 ft/min) to provide a clearer, generalised overview of velocities across the system."


MESSAGE user "What’s the method for creating pipe colour fill legends?"
MESSAGE assistant "Duplicate your HVAC floor plan view, rename it (e.g., 'Pipe Flow Rates'), then insert a pipe colour fill legend. Edit the scheme, duplicate it, and change the scheme to display 'Flow'. Adjust the fill display (contour or internal) by editing the highlighter fill width and contour fill values."


MESSAGE user "How can I adjust the pipe colour fill display for better visibility?"
MESSAGE assistant "Edit the pipe colour fill legend scheme. For smaller pipes, set the highlighter fill width (e.g., 1/32 inch) to create an external contour. For larger pipes, increase the contour fill value (e.g., 1 inch) to move the fill inside the pipe."


MESSAGE user "How do colour fill legends update with system changes?"
MESSAGE assistant "Both duct and pipe colour fill legends dynamically update as system properties (flow, velocity, size) change. This allows you to immediately see the impact of design changes and ensures your mechanical systems meet design criteria."


MESSAGE user "What are duct and pipe placeholders used for in early MEP design stages?"
MESSAGE assistant "You use duct and pipe placeholders to create indicative mechanical layouts, eliminating the need to detail sizes, fittings, or coordination. They carry the same intelligence as regular ducts and pipes but are represented by single lines, allowing for quick conceptual layouts that can be detailed later."


MESSAGE user "Where can I find duct and pipe placeholders?"
MESSAGE assistant "Duct and pipe placeholders can be found on the Duct Placeholder panel of the Systems tab for ducts and on the Plumbing and Piping panel of the Systems tab for pipes."


MESSAGE user "Can I set duct types and sizes when using duct placeholders?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes. Even though placeholders simplify the layout, you can still select duct types from the type selector and set duct sizes from the options bar when using duct placeholders."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust duct placeholder elevations?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the Elevation option in the Options Bar. Set the elevation as required, and for risers, you can change the elevation to zero and apply the change."


MESSAGE user "How do you create a new duct system type?"
