MESSAGE user "What are analytical panels?"
MESSAGE assistant "Analytical panels represent simplified versions of plate-like structural elements such as floors, slabs, and walls. They contain the data required for structural analysis."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the geometry of an analytical panel?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the panel, then click and drag a node to move it. Moving a node adjusts the positions of connected elements and changes the panel geometry."


MESSAGE user "How can I modify a panel's geometry without affecting connected elements?"
MESSAGE assistant "To modify only the panel, select it, then from the ribbon, go to the Modify | Analytical Panels tab and click 'Edit Boundary'. You can then move edges and click 'Finish Edit Mode' to save changes."


MESSAGE user "What are the middle panel controls on an analytical panel?"
MESSAGE assistant "The middle panel controls allow you to adjust the geometry of the panel directly. Select a control and drag it to modify the shape without using nodes."


MESSAGE user "How do I create an energy model?"
MESSAGE assistant "To create an energy model, ensure you have defined analytical systems and system zones. Then, go to the Analyse tab, and from the Energy Optimisation panel, select 'Create Energy Model'."


MESSAGE user "Where do I find the energy optimisation settings?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Analyse tab on the ribbon, and under the Energy Optimisation panel, you'll find the energy settings. Set the mode to 'Use Conceptual Masses and Building Elements' for flexibility."


MESSAGE user "How do I set HVAC system assumptions for the energy analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the energy settings dialogue, under Advanced Options, set the HVAC system to an option like 'Central VAV'. This applies a range of assumptions to the analysis."


MESSAGE user "How do I apply thermal properties from actual building elements in Revit’s energy model?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Energy Settings dialogue, set the Material Thermal Properties to 'Detailed Elements' to use thermal properties from real building elements."


MESSAGE user "How can I adjust building space types for energy analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Manage tab, select MEP Settings, and then choose 'Building/Space Type Settings'. From there, you can assign types like 'hospital or healthcare' and adjust related parameters."


MESSAGE user "How do I add a space for energy analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "From the Analyse tab, select the 'Space' command. Set the upper limit to 'Roof' with an offset of zero, and place the space in the desired area of the floor plan."


MESSAGE user "How do I change space properties such as cooling set point or space type?"
MESSAGE assistant "When you select a space, the Properties palette lets you change the type of area and change values such as the cooling set point and the outdoor air method."


MESSAGE user "How do I improve the quality of analytical spaces in an energy model?"
MESSAGE assistant "Reduce the 'Analytical Space Resolution' and 'Analytical Surface Resolution' values in the Energy Settings dialogue."


MESSAGE user "How do I open the System Browser?"
MESSAGE assistant "Right-click anywhere in the interface, select 'Browsers', and then pick 'System Browser' to launch the system browser."


MESSAGE user "How do I display analytical systems in the System Browser?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, set the dropdown menu to 'Analytical Systems' to view and manage analytical systems."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign zone equipment to a single analytical space?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the analytical space, then under zone equipment in the Properties window, set the 'Behaviour' parameter to 'One Per Space'."


MESSAGE user "How do I add the zone equipment to multiple analytical spaces?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the analytical space, and in the Properties window, change the 'Behaviour' value to 'Group Spaces on Equipment'."


MESSAGE user "How do I remove zone equipment from an analytical space?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, right-click the analytical space, review the options, and select 'Remove Equipment'."


MESSAGE user "How do I move an analytical space to different zone equipment?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, right-click the analytical space, select 'Move To', and choose the desired zone equipment from the list."


MESSAGE user "How do I copy an analytical space to multiple zone equipment?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, right-click the analytical space, select 'Copy', and assign it to the additional zone equipment as needed."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign zone equipment to an entire system zone?"
MESSAGE assistant "Switch to the 'System Zones' view, select the analytical zone, and under the Energy Analysis properties, use the dropdown menu to change the zone equipment."


MESSAGE user "What are analytical systems used for?"
MESSAGE assistant "Without incorporating real components into the model, analytical methods enable mechanical engineers to specify air and water loops, allocate zone equipment, and assess various design alternatives."


MESSAGE user "How do I access the System Browser for analytical systems?"
MESSAGE assistant "From the View tab, select 'User Interface', then choose 'System Browser'. In the System Browser, set the dropdown menu to 'Analytical Systems'."


MESSAGE user "What are the benefits of using analytical systems early in a project?"
MESSAGE assistant "Analytical systems allow flexible, fast adjustments to equipment, zones, and connections, making it easy to explore design options without impacting the physical model."


MESSAGE user "How do I review the mechanical flow data in a physical system?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select a section of ductwork and check the 'Mechanical Flow' area in the Properties palette to view flow rates, velocity, and pressure values."


MESSAGE user "How do I use rooms or spaces when creating the energy analytical model?"
MESSAGE assistant "To use rooms or spaces, go to the Analyse tab, Energy Optimisation panel, and select 'Energy Settings'. In the dialogue, set the mode to 'Use Rooms or Spaces'."


MESSAGE user "How can I determine if the energy analysis uses rooms or spaces?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Advanced Energy Settings dialogue, under 'Export Category', choose either 'Rooms' or 'Spaces' depending on your preference. This determines whether Revit uses room or space information in the analysis."


MESSAGE user "How do I enable detailed material thermal properties?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Energy Settings dialogue, open Advanced Energy Settings, and under 'Material Thermal Properties', enable 'Detailed Elements'. Make sure all material thermal data is accurate to avoid errors."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign zone equipment to analytical spaces?"
MESSAGE assistant "Ensure the System Browser is open and set to 'Analytical Systems'. Select the analytical space, and in the Properties window, adjust the 'Behaviour parameter' to assign zone equipment."


MESSAGE user "Can I apply the same zone equipment to multiple analytical spaces?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, in the Properties window, change the 'Behaviour' value to 'Group Spaces on Equipment'. This applies the same zone equipment to multiple analytical spaces."


MESSAGE user "How do I remove an analytical space from zone equipment?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, right-click the analytical space, select 'Remove Equipment', and the space will no longer be assigned to zone equipment."


MESSAGE user "How do I move an analytical space to different zone equipment?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, right-click the analytical space, choose 'Move To', and select the desired zone equipment."


MESSAGE user "Is it possible to assign a zone equipment to an entire system zone?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, switch to the 'System Zones' view, select the analytical zone, and under Energy Analysis properties, change the Zone Equipment from the dropdown menu."


MESSAGE user "How do I upload my model to Insight for energy analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "From the Analyse tab, Carbon Insight panel, select 'Analyse'. Follow the prompts to log in, update the analytical model if necessary, and continue to upload your model for analysis."


MESSAGE user "Where can I view the results of my carbon analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once the analysis runs, click 'View Analysis' to open the Autodesk Insight page in your web browser. Here, you can monitor progress and review results on the Insight dashboard."

MESSAGE user "How do I create an energy analytical model?"
MESSAGE assistant "To create an energy analytical model, go to the Analyse tab on the ribbon, and in the Energy Optimisation panel, select 'Create Energy Model'. A warning dialogue will appear; click 'Create the Energy Analytical Model' to proceed."


MESSAGE user "What should I do if the energy analytical model creation is taking too long?"
MESSAGE assistant "The time required depends on the size and complexity of your model. Consider adjusting the analytical space resolution and analytical surface resolution in the energy settings to reduce processing time."


MESSAGE user "How can I modify the analytical space and surface resolutions?"
MESSAGE assistant "With the model open, go to the Analyse tab, Energy Optimisation panel, and select 'Energy Settings'. In the dialogue, adjust the Analytical Space Resolution and Analytical Surface Resolution values to balance accuracy and processing time."


MESSAGE user "Why is it warning about linked models not being room-bounding?"
MESSAGE assistant "Revit uses room-bounding elements to generate the energy analytical model. If you do not set linked models as room-bounding, the analysis may exclude them. Adjust their room bounding properties as needed."


MESSAGE user "How do I delete an existing energy analytical model?"
MESSAGE assistant "From the Analyse tab, in the Energy Optimisation panel, select 'Delete Energy Model'. This removes the existing analytical model and allows you to create a new one."


MESSAGE user "What are analytical spaces in the energy analytical model?"
MESSAGE assistant "Analytical spaces represent discrete air volumes that experience heat gain or loss due to factors like occupancy, lighting, HVAC, and heat exchange. They are shown in blue in the model."


MESSAGE user "How do I view analytical surfaces?"
MESSAGE assistant "Press 'VG' to open the Visibility/Graphic Overrides dialogue. Go to the Analytical Model Categories tab and enable Analytical Surfaces to display them."


MESSAGE user "How can I specify material thermal properties for energy analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Analyse tab, Energy Optimisation panel, and select 'Energy Settings'. Scroll down, and under Advanced, click 'Edit'. In the Advanced Energy Settings dialogue, configure the Conceptual Types, Schematic Types, and Detailed Elements options."


MESSAGE user "What is the difference between conceptual types, schematic types, and detailed elements for thermal properties?"
MESSAGE assistant "Conceptual types are default thermal properties used when others are not defined. Schematic types override conceptual types during the schematic design. Detailed elements override both when specific material thermal properties are assigned in the Materials Library."


MESSAGE user "Does the energy analytical model automatically update with the architectural model?"
MESSAGE assistant "No, the energy analytical model does not regenerate automatically with architectural model changes. You need to manually delete and recreate it if the design changes."


MESSAGE user "How do I start creating analytical systems?"
MESSAGE assistant "First, make sure your model has designated all the necessary system zones and analytical spaces according to each discipline. Then, on the View ribbon, in the Windows panel, expand the 'User Interface' drop-down and select 'System Browser'."


MESSAGE user "What do I do in the System Browser?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, at the top, expand the drop-down and select 'Analytical Systems'. This will show you the available tools for creating analytical systems."


MESSAGE user "What tools are available in the System Browser?"
MESSAGE assistant "There are three tools available: 'Add Zone Equipment', 'Add Air System', and 'Add Water Loop'."


MESSAGE user "How do I add zone equipment?"
MESSAGE assistant "Click 'Add Zone Equipment'. In the Properties palette, specify the following: Equipment Type as 'Series Fan Powered Box', Behaviour as 'Group Spaces on Equipment', and Heating Coil as 'Electric Resistance'."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign zone equipment to a zone?"
MESSAGE assistant "With the Unassigned zone selected in the floor plan, it will be named 'System-Zone'. In the Properties Palette, set the Zone Equipment."


MESSAGE user "How do I add an air system?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the System Browser, click 'Add Air System'. In the Properties palette, Heat Exchanger is 'Enthalpy', Preheat Coil is 'Electric Resistance', Cooling Coil is 'Chilled Water', Heating Coil is 'Hot Water', and Fan is 'Variable Volume'."


MESSAGE user "How do I add a water loop?"
MESSAGE assistant "Click 'Add Water Loop' in the System Browser. In the Properties palette, specify the Name as 'Chilled Water', Loop Type as 'Chilled Water', and Chiller Type as 'Air Cooled'. Then, add another water loop for hot water, specifying the name as 'Hot Water' and the loop type as 'Hot Water'."


MESSAGE user "How do I associate my air system with water loops?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Properties palette, select the water loops you created for the Chilled Water Loop and the Heating Hot Water Loop. This associates your analytical air system with the hot- and cold-water loops."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign an air system to zone equipment?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Properties palette, select 'AHU 1' for the Air System. Now, your zone equipment is linked to the air system."



MESSAGE user "====================================================COMMENT========================================================"
MESSAGE assistant "Is related to: https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/create-duct-systems-in-revit"



MESSAGE user "How do I create duct systems to connect air terminals?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once you have placed air terminal components in your model, there are two methods to create the duct systems to connect them. The method you use depends on how you select the air terminals."


MESSAGE user "What’s the method to create duct systems?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select a single air terminal with a duct connector. Then, on the contextual ribbon, click 'Duct'. Ensure the connector has the flow direction set to 'In' for it to behave properly in the duct system. In the Create Duct System dialogue, set the System type to 'Supply Air', enable 'Open in System Editor', and click OK. Then, on the contextual ribbon, click 'Add to System'. Now, in the drawing area, select any air terminals you want to add to your system, either individually or using an alternate selection method. Then, click 'Select Equipment' on the contextual ribbon and choose the fan coil unit serving your air terminals."


MESSAGE user "What’s another method for creating a duct system?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select all your air terminals first. Then, on the contextual ribbon, click 'Duct'. In the Create Duct System dialogue, select 'Supply Air' for the System type, enable 'Open in System Editor', and click OK."


MESSAGE user "What do I do after closing the dialogue?"
MESSAGE assistant "After closing the dialogue, click 'Select Equipment' in the contextual ribbon and select the fan coil unit serving your air terminals."


MESSAGE user "How do I generate the layout for the duct system?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once your duct system is created, you can use the 'Generate Layout' tool. You can also switch to the Duct Systems contextual ribbon to access instances and type properties."



MESSAGE user "=====================================================COMMENT========================================================"
MESSAGE assistant "Is related to: https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/place-air-terminals-in-revit"



MESSAGE user "How do I add components to my system after creating zones, spaces, and an air system?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once you've created system zones, spaces, and an air system, you can add components like air terminals to the system. This exercise will show you how to place air terminals and set their space parameters for more accurate analysis results."


MESSAGE user "Why do I need to place air terminals?"
MESSAGE assistant "Devices like air terminals are important because they provide data used in calculating the loads for the spaces in your duct system. This data tracks the supply, return, and exhaust air in each room, which helps you select the correct air terminal sizes."


MESSAGE user "How do I place an air terminal?"
MESSAGE assistant "On the ribbon, go to the 'Systems' tab, then in the HVAC panel, click 'Air Terminal'. From the Type Selector, choose a face-based family type."


MESSAGE user "Do I need to select a different type of air terminal?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, for this step, choose '24 x 24 Face 12 x 12 Connection Supply Diffuser'. This type is a non-hosted family, so the Placement panel won’t appear in the contextual ribbon. Set the level to 'Ground Floor' and the elevation to 9'-0', and then click the ceiling to place the air terminal."


MESSAGE user "What should I do after placing the air terminal?"
MESSAGE assistant "Next, select the air terminal, go to the 'Modify' ribbon, and click 'Align' to align the air terminal to the ceiling grid. You can also adjust the visibility by deselecting the arrow parameters in the Properties palette to remove arrows from the view."


MESSAGE user "How do I check the airflow for the space?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the space where the air terminals are placed. Pay attention to the 'Actual Supply Airflow' parameter, which sums the airflows of all the terminals within that space."


MESSAGE user "What if the space isn't accounting for the airflow correctly?"
MESSAGE assistant "If the space isn't accounting for the air terminal flow but your terminals are placed correctly, you can adjust the room calculation point to be inside the space. To do this, select the air terminal, click 'Edit Family' in the contextual ribbon, and make the necessary adjustments."


MESSAGE user "=====================================================COMMENT========================================================"
MESSAGE assistant "Is related to: https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/making-changes-to-mechanical-systems and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/the-mechanical-analysis-workflow and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/place-mechanical-equipment-in-revit and one other I forgot to link."



MESSAGE user "How do I control the flow direction at a connector?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the connector in the Family Editor. Under the connector properties, set the flow direction to 'out' if air or fluid is leaving the component, or 'in' if it’s entering."


MESSAGE user "Why is the airflow at the fan coil unit calculated automatically?"
MESSAGE assistant "The airflow is calculated because the flow configuration at the supply fan coil unit connector is set to 'Calculate'. This ensures that the system adjusts automatically based on connected elements like air terminals."


MESSAGE user "What happens if I change the flow rate at an air terminal?"
MESSAGE assistant "Any change to the flow rate at an air terminal will result in updated calculated values at the fan coil unit, ensuring the system maintains accurate flow distribution."


MESSAGE user "How do I configure flow distribution between multiple pumps?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Family Editor, set the connector configuration to 'System' for each pump. Then associate a 'Flow Factor' family parameter to control the proportion of flow through each pump."


MESSAGE user "Where can I create and control the 'Flow Factor' parameter?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can create the 'Flow Factor' parameter in the Family Editor by selecting 'Associate Family Parameter' on the connector’s flow settings, creating a new instance parameter, and grouping it under Mechanical Flow."


MESSAGE user "What does disabling 'Closed Loop Piping Networks' do?"
MESSAGE assistant "Disabling 'Closed Loop Piping Networks' in Mechanical Settings allows for open system flow calculations, giving you control over how flow is distributed without automatic balancing."


MESSAGE user "How do I set up a conceptual mass for energy analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the 'Massing & Site' tab to create conceptual masses based on the architect’s model. This simplifies the model for early-stage analysis and enables you to quickly apply energy settings."


MESSAGE user "What are analytical spaces and surfaces in energy models?"
MESSAGE assistant "Analytical spaces represent air volumes needing heating or cooling, while analytical surfaces define material thermal properties and heat transfer characteristics. Both are essential for accurate energy simulation."


MESSAGE user "How can I convert duct placeholders to real ductwork?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the duct placeholder system using the Tab key. Then, use the 'Convert Placeholder' option from the ribbon. After conversion, you can edit, resize, and reposition the ductwork as needed."


MESSAGE user "What steps do I follow to convert pipe placeholders?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the placeholder piping using the Tab key. Set the pipe type, then click 'Convert Placeholder' on the ribbon. After conversion, adjust elevation, size, and fittings to finalise the network."


MESSAGE user "How do I load mechanical equipment families into the project?"
MESSAGE assistant "On the 'Insert' ribbon, click 'Load Autodesk Family', navigate to Mechanical MEP > Water-Side Components > Pumps, select the desired pump families, and click 'Load'."


MESSAGE user "How do I place mechanical equipment like pumps?"
MESSAGE assistant "After loading the pump family, go to the 'Systems' ribbon, click 'Mechanical Equipment', select the pump type, set its level and elevation, and place it in the drawing area. Use the SPACEBAR to rotate as needed."



