MESSAGE assistant "Is related to: https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/revit-worksets and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/controlling-workset-visibility and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/creating-and-assigning-worksets and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/create-design-option-sets-and-options"



MESSAGE user "What is a workset?"
MESSAGE assistant "A workset is a collection of elements within a workshared project. Worksets allow multiple users to collaborate by owning or borrowing elements."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new workset?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Collaborate ribbon; in the Manage Collaboration panel, click 'Worksets'. In the Worksets dialogue, click 'New', type the name of the new workset, leave 'Visible in all views' selected if needed, and click OK."


MESSAGE user "Who can edit elements within a workset?"
MESSAGE assistant "Initially, only the owner of the workset (the user who created it) can edit its elements. However, after synchronising with the central model, other users can borrow elements if the workset is marked as 'Not Editable'."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign elements to a specific workset?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the element, and in the Properties palette, under Identity Data, expand the Workset dropdown and select the desired workset."


MESSAGE user "What happens if I create an element when a certain workset is active?"
MESSAGE assistant "Any new element you place is automatically assigned to the active workset. You can change the active workset from the Manage Collaboration panel or from the status bar."


MESSAGE user "How can I visually distinguish elements from different worksets?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can use the 'Grey Inactive Worksets' option on the Manage Collaboration panel or in the Worksets dialogue to visually distinguish elements in your active worksets."


MESSAGE user "What should I do before closing a central model?"
MESSAGE assistant "Before closing the central model, go to the Collaborate ribbon, Synchronise panel, and select 'Synchronise with Central' and 'Relinquish All Mine' to free up elements for other team members."


MESSAGE user "How do I temporarily hide elements from a specific workset in a view?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the view’s Properties palette, click 'Edit Visibility/Graphics Overrides', go to the 'Worksets' tab, and uncheck or hide the desired workset."


MESSAGE user "How do I check which workset an element belongs to?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the element and look in the Properties palette under the Identity Data panel to see its assigned workset."


MESSAGE user "How do I use colour coding to identify worksets?"
MESSAGE assistant "On the view control bar, click 'Worksharing Display' and choose 'Worksets'. Each workset will be colour-coded. You can customise the colours by selecting 'Worksharing Display Settings'."


MESSAGE user "Can I move an element to a different workset after it’s created?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, select the element, and in the Properties palette under Identity Data, change its Workset to the desired one."


MESSAGE user "What is the benefit of closing worksets?"
MESSAGE assistant "Closing worksets hides their elements from the current view, making it easier to focus on specific parts of the project and reducing file load."


MESSAGE user "How do I open specific worksets when opening a project?"
MESSAGE assistant "When opening a project, select 'Specify' next to worksets options, then choose which worksets you want to open before clicking OK."


MESSAGE user "How do I create an alternative layout for the upper floor?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Level 2 Floor Plan'. Then, navigate to the Manage ribbon tab, and in the Design Options panel, click 'Design Options'. Create a new option set and rename it to something like 'Upper Floor'. Add new options within this set, which will act as containers for the different layout variations."


MESSAGE user "How do I move existing elements into a design option?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the elements you want to include in the design options. Go to the Manage ribbon tab and click 'Add to Set' in the Design Options panel. Choose the desired option set, and check the options where you'd like to copy the elements."


MESSAGE user "How do I edit elements in a specific design option?"
MESSAGE assistant "First, set the design option as active by selecting it in the Design Options dialogue. Once active, you can modify the elements within that option without affecting the main model or other options."


MESSAGE user "How do I make one of the design options the default view in the main model?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Design Options dialogue, select the design option you want to make default and click 'Make Primary'. This sets it as the primary option, so it will display when you're viewing the main model."


MESSAGE user "How do I create an alternative design for the roof?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Manage tab, open Design Options, and create a new Option Set named something like 'Roof'. Add a new option, then activate it. To create a new roof, go to the Architecture tab, select 'Roof by Footprint', and sketch the roof. This new roof will automatically be part of the active design option."


MESSAGE user "How do I view the different roof design options?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the Design Options dropdown in the status bar at the bottom of the screen or the Manage tab to switch between options. Each option will display the corresponding roof design based on what's set as active or primary."


MESSAGE user "Why do certain elements disappear when I switch design options?"
MESSAGE assistant "If an element is only part of one design option and not the others, it will disappear when you switch to an option where it hasn't been added. You can control which options include each element by using the 'Add to Set' feature."



