MESSAGE assistant "Is related to: https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/create-shared-parameters and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/about-shared-parameters and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/setting-up-shared-coordinates and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/enabling-worksharing-and-sharing-project-files and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/set-up-a-shared-coordinate-system-in-revit"



MESSAGE user "How do I acquire coordinates from a DWG file?"
MESSAGE assistant "To acquire coordinates from a linked DWG file, go to the 'Manage' ribbon tab. In the 'Project Location' panel, click 'Coordinates' and then select 'Acquire Coordinates'. Zoom out and select the DWG file to acquire the coordinates. After this, you will see that the coordinates have been successfully updated."


MESSAGE user "How do I update the model's orientation?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'View' tab and select 'Orientation'. If the view is set to true north, you can change it to project north to adjust the rotation to how you originally modelled it."


MESSAGE user "How do I publish coordinates from my site model to other linked models?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Manage' ribbon tab, and under the 'Project Location' panel, click 'Coordinates' and select 'Publish Coordinates'. Choose the project you want to publish the coordinates to, then confirm the internal site and click 'OK'. The coordinates will now be shared with the selected model."


MESSAGE user "How do I link another model into my project using shared coordinates?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Insert' ribbon tab and click 'Link Revit'. Select the model you want to link and choose 'Auto by Shared Coordinates' for positioning. Once you click 'Open', the linked model will automatically align with the existing models based on shared coordinates."


MESSAGE user "What is work sharing, and how do I enable it?"
MESSAGE assistant "Work sharing allows multiple users to collaborate on the same project. To enable it, go to the 'Collaborate' ribbon tab and click 'Collaborate' in the 'Manage Collaboration' panel. You can choose to collaborate either using BIM 360 or within your network. After confirming, work sharing will be enabled, and you can start collaborating on the model."


MESSAGE user "How do I save a central model?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Quick Access Toolbar' and click 'Save'.  It will prompt you to confirm saving the project as a central model. Choose 'Yes' to continue, and your model will be saved as a central model, allowing other users to work in local files."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new shared coordinate system?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Autodesk Point Layout' tab and click 'Create Coordinate.' Enter the XYZ values for two known points, such as grid intersections, and paste them into the respective fields. Once the coordinates are correctly entered, you’ll be prompted to name the coordinate system, and after confirming, it will be set as the current coordinate system for the project."


MESSAGE user "How do I switch between Project North and True North?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'View' tab, select 'Orientation', and choose the desired orientation. Changing from True North to Project North will rotate the view to match the original orientation of the model."


MESSAGE user "How do I work in a local file with work sharing enabled?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once work sharing is enabled and the model is saved as a central file, you need to work in a local copy. To do this, close the central file and open the model again. It will prompt you to create a local copy. After confirming, you’ll be working in a local file, which is stored on your machine while the central model remains on the network."


MESSAGE user "How do I use the 'Create Coordinate' tool in Autodesk Point Layout?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Autodesk Point Layout' tab and click 'Create Coordinate.' Select the first known point and input its XYZ values from the spreadsheet. Continue this process for the second point, making sure to maximise the distance between them. After entering the values, it will prompt you to name the coordinate system, and once confirmed, it will be set as the project’s coordinate system."


MESSAGE user "How do I start a new project?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the home screen, select 'New', and for the template file, choose 'Structural Analysis Default'. Then, click 'OK' to create your project."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new family?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the File ribbon, hover over 'New', and select 'Family'. In the New Family dialogue box, choose the 'Generic Model' template and click 'Open'."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the category of a family?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Create ribbon, click on 'Family Category and Parameters', and select the appropriate category—in this case, 'Structural Foundation'. Click 'OK' to apply."


MESSAGE user "Where can I find built-inparameters in a family?"
MESSAGE assistant "Built-in parameters are accessible by clicking 'Family Types' on the Create ribbon. For example, selecting 'Structural Foundation' reveals parameters like length, width, and foundation thickness."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a shared parameter file?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Manage ribbon and select 'Shared Parameters'. In the dialogue box, click 'Create', name your file and click 'Save'."


MESSAGE user "How do I organise shared parameters?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Shared Parameters dialogue, after creating a file, click 'New Group' to categorise parameters. For example, name the group 'Foundations' to keep related parameters together."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new shared parameter?"
MESSAGE assistant "Inside your shared parameter group, click 'New' to create a parameter. Give it a unique name like 'F_Length', set the discipline to 'Common', and the type to 'Length'. Click 'OK' when done."


MESSAGE user "Why should I avoid naming conflicts with built-in parameters?"
MESSAGE assistant "You should avoid using names like length, width, or foundation thickness for shared parameters, as these are built-in parameters, and conflicts could disrupt scheduling and tagging."


MESSAGE user "Can multiple projects use shared parameters?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, shared parameters are stored externally and can be used across multiple families and projects, ensuring consistency. They can be tagged, scheduled, and managed centrally."


MESSAGE user "What happens if I delete a shared parameter?"
MESSAGE assistant "If a shared parameter is deleted, any tags and schedules referencing it will become invalid and need to be recreated, so shared parameters should be managed carefully."


MESSAGE user "How do tags read shared parameters in families?"
MESSAGE assistant "Tags can be set up to read shared parameters like length, width, and thickness. When a family instance is tagged, the tag will automatically display these shared parameter values."


MESSAGE user "How do I change a parameter from type to instance?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the parameter, click 'Edit Parameter', and change its settings from 'Type' to 'Instance'. This allows you to adjust the parameter value per instance rather than globally."


MESSAGE user "What visual cue indicates an instance parameter in the Family Types dialogue?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can easily distinguish instance parameters from type parameters in the Family Typesdialogue by marking them with '(default)' beside their names."


MESSAGE user "What happens when you convert length and width to instance parameters?"
MESSAGE assistant "Once length and width are converted to instance parameters, shape handles appear on the family in the project, allowing you to graphically adjust dimensions per instance."


MESSAGE user "How do shared parameters affect schedules?"
MESSAGE assistant "Schedules automatically update when shared parameters change. For example, modifying foundation dimensions will reflect immediately in the foundation schedule without needing manual updates."


MESSAGE user "Where should the shared parameter file be stored?"
MESSAGE assistant "The shared parameter file should typically be stored on a file server, allowing all team members access while keeping it centrally managed and, ideally, read-only to avoid accidental changes."



MESSAGE user "=====================================================COMMENT========================================================"
MESSAGE assistant "Is related to: https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/managing-refurbishment-projects-with-phasing and https://www.autodesk.com/learn/ondemand/tutorial/assigning-phases-to-objects-using-filters"



MESSAGE user "How do I use phases?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the Phasing panel, click 'Phases'. Here, you can define your project phases, such as existing and new construction. You can also use phase filters to control how objects are displayed, showing new, existing, demolished, or temporary statuses for objects in different phases."


MESSAGE user "How can I assign an object to be demolished?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the object and go to its properties. Change the 'Phase Created' property to the appropriate phase and set the 'Phase Demolished' to the new construction phase. Alternatively, you can use the Demolish tool from the Modify ribbon and select the object to demolish it in the current phase."


MESSAGE user "How do I create new walls and doors during construction?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Architecture ribbon tab and select the 'Wall' tool. Draw the wall where needed. To add doors, select the 'Door' tool from the Architecture tab and place them in the walls. If these objects are in the new construction phase, they won’t be visible in existing views, but they will appear in new views that have the new construction phase assigned."


MESSAGE user "How do I create temporary objects?"
MESSAGE assistant "Create it in the new construction phase. Then, use the Demolish tool from the Modify ribbon to demolish it in the same phase. You can verify that the object is temporary by checking that its properties show that it is created and destroyed in the same phase."


MESSAGE user "How do I control what is displayed in a phase view?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use phase filters. Go to the 'Phases' dialogue under the Manage tab, where you can set the phase for the view. Choose filters like 'Show All' or 'Show Complete' to determine how new, existing, demolished, or temporary objects are shown in your view."


MESSAGE user "How can I compare the existing and completed layouts?"
MESSAGE assistant "Duplicate your 'Level 1 New' view and rename it 'Level 1 Complete'. Then, change the phase filter to 'Show Complete' to hide demolished and temporary objects. You can place both the 'Level 1 Existing' and 'Level 1 Complete' views on the same sheet for side-by-side comparison."


MESSAGE user "How do I handle demolished objects in the view?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the 'Show Complete' phase filter, which will hide demolished and temporary objects. This allows you to see only the existing and new objects in the view, helping you focus on the current and completed construction work."


MESSAGE user "What happens when I change the phase of an object?"
MESSAGE assistant "It will inherit the phase status (e.g., existing, demolished, new construction) based on the phase of the view you're working in. For example, if you create a wall in the 'Existing' view, the wall will inherit the 'Existing' phase and will be treated accordingly in the phase filters."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign a phase filter to a view?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the view and open its properties. Under the 'Phasing' panel, you can choose the phase for that view and select a filter such as 'Show All' or 'Show Complete'. The filter will control how objects in different phases are displayed in the view."


MESSAGE user "How do I display demolished objects in a phase view?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the 'Show All' phase filter. This filter will show all objects, including demolished and temporary ones. You can apply this filter to a view to see the demolished objects in red with dashed lines, indicating their removal in the construction process."



