MESSAGE user "How do I create a new pile type for a pile cap?"
MESSAGE assistant "Expand the 'Families' folder in the Project Browser and navigate to 'Structural Foundations' and expand 'Pile Steel Pipe'. Right-click on the type you want to duplicate, select 'Duplicate', and name the new pile type. Afterward, edit the type properties and adjust dimensions, such as the pile diameter and depth, to your specifications."


MESSAGE user "How do I modify the elevation at the bottom of a pile cap?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the pile and pile cap. In the properties palette, you'll see 'Elevation at Bottom'. If it is showing the bottom of the pile instead of the pile cap, go to the 'Context Ribbon', select 'Edit Family', and enable the 'Cap' parameter. Then, load the changes into the project, and the elevation at the bottom will update to show the underside of the pile cap."


MESSAGE user "What is the purpose of the 'Material for Model Behaviour' parameter in a foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "It controls how elements, like foundations, interact with other elements in the model. It determines whether the elements join together or remain separate."


MESSAGE user "How can I adjust the physical dimensions of an isolated foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "The physical dimensions of an isolated foundation are controlled using type parameters. To adjust them, select the foundation and go to the 'Properties Palette'. You can modify the dimensions, including the length, width, and thickness, in the 'Type Properties' dialogue box. You can also create new family types for different sizes and assign specific type marks for each type."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new pile cap and pile?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select an existing pile cap and right-click to select 'Create Similar'. Place the pile cap at the desired grid intersection. In the 'Type Properties' dialogue box, duplicate the pile cap type and give it a new name. Then, in the pile type dropdown, select the new pile type you want to use, adjust the dimensions, and click 'OK' to finish creating your new pile cap and pile."


MESSAGE user "What parameters control the shape and size of a pile cap?"
MESSAGE assistant "The parameters that control the shape and size of a pile cap include the length, width, cutoff clearance, and foundation thickness. You can find these in the 'Type Properties' dialogue box after selecting the pile cap. You can adjust these values to change the size of the pile cap, and for the pile itself, you can select different pile types within the family."


MESSAGE user "How do I edit the pile cap type?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the pile cap and go to the 'Type Properties' dialogue box. From there, click 'Edit Type', and you can duplicate the existing pile cap type to create a new one. Afterward, you can modify the dimensions, such as the length, width, and foundation thickness. Once done, click 'OK' to apply the changes."


MESSAGE user "What does the 'Cap' parameter control in a foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "The 'Cap' parameter controls whether the elevation at the bottom of the foundation is shown at the underside of the cap instead of the bottom of the foundation. Enabling the 'Cap' parameter allows the model to correctly display the elevation from the underside of the cap, ensuring accuracy in the model's measurements."


MESSAGE user "How do I add additional piles to a pile cap?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the pile cap and right-click to select 'Create Similar'. Place the new pile cap at the desired grid intersections. You can repeat this process to add as many piles as needed. Once placed, you can modify the pile properties if necessary, ensuring each pile is correctly nested within the cap."


MESSAGE user "How do I inspect the new family type after modifying it?"
MESSAGE assistant "Switch the view to a 3D foundation view. This allows you to visually inspect how the new family type looks in the model and ensures everything is placed correctly, including pile caps and piles."


MESSAGE user "How do I flip the orientation of a retaining wall foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and press the space bar. This will flip the foundation automatically. If the foundation is already in the correct orientation but you need to flip it specifically, select the foundation and use the flip command available in the options."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the height of a retaining wall foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall. Then, use the shape handles at the top and bottom of the wall to change the height or depth. As you adjust the height of the wall, the foundation will automatically follow the changes."


MESSAGE user "How do I extend the length of a retaining wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the plan view and select the wall. Then, drag the wall length by using the drag wall length feature. The foundation will automatically adapt to the new length of the wall."


MESSAGE user "How do I place an isolated foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Structure ribbon and select the Foundation panel. Then click on the 'Isolated Foundation' tool. From the Type Selector, choose the foundation type, and then place it by clicking at grid intersections or structural columns. You can also orientate the foundation using the space bar."


MESSAGE user "How can I place multiple isolated foundations at once?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the 'Place Isolated Foundations at Grids' option. Select the grid intersections, and a preview of the foundations will appear. Then, click Finish to finalise the placement."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the position of an isolated foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the foundation and use the temporary dimensions that appear. You can drag the dimension lines to change the offset and then make these dimensions permanent by selecting the appropriate icon."


MESSAGE user "How do I modify the base level of a structural column and see its effect on foundations?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the column, and in the properties palette, adjust the base offset. The foundations attached to the column will automatically move to match the new base level, and you will receive a warning confirming this change."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a custom foundation element?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use an in-place family. Go to the Structure ribbon, select 'Model In Place', and choose the family category as 'Structural Foundations'. After that, model the foundation using solid or void extrusion tools, set the material properties, and finalise the creation process."


MESSAGE user "How do I join an in-place family to other foundations?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the in-place family and use the 'Join' command from the Modifier ribbon. Then, select the foundation elements you wish to join it with. Once you have joined the foundation elements, you can release the join command by clicking 'Modify'."


MESSAGE user "How do I copy an in-place foundation element?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the foundation and click on the 'Copy' command in the context ribbon. Ensure that 'Multiple' is selected in the options bar. Then, define the start and end points for the copy, and finalise by clicking 'Modify' to release the command."


MESSAGE user "How do I place wall foundations?"
MESSAGE assistant "Open your site plan under 'Structural Plans' in the project browser. Then, on the 'Structure' ribbon, select 'Wall Foundation'. You can choose the foundation type, such as a bearing or retaining footing, from the type selector. Simply select the wall in your plan or 3D view to place the foundation, which will automatically align with the wall."


MESSAGE user "What is the difference between a bearing footing and a retaining footing?"
MESSAGE assistant "A bearing footing is centred around the wall's centreline and has a simple width and thickness. A retaining footing, on the other hand, has additional heel and toe lengths, which make it eccentric and provide more stability for retaining walls. This allows for better management of the wall’s forces, especially for taller or sloped retaining walls."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the type of a wall foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the foundation in your project. In the properties palette, click on 'Edit Type' to open the type properties dialogue box. You can duplicate the current type, change the dimensions, and adjust other parameters. For example, you can change the foundation thickness or the concrete grade before applying it to your model."


MESSAGE user "How do I fix wall foundations around door openings?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the type properties of the wall foundation. In the 'Dimensions' section, check the 'Do not break inserts' option. This will stop the foundation from breaking around openings like doors or windows, keeping the foundation continuous."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the eccentricity of a foundation under a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the foundation and go to the 'Instance Properties'. In the 'Eccentricity' field, you can set a value to shift the foundation off the centreline of the wall. This is usefulfor walls that have different materials, such as a composite wall with brick and metal studs."


MESSAGE user "How can I see the analytical model of a wall foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Visibility Graphics' settings under the 'View' ribbon. In the dialogue box, uncheck the visibility of the analytical walls and structural loads. This will give you a clear view of the analytical wall foundation in your project, which is displayed as a simple line representing the foundation."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the length of a wall foundation?"
MESSAGE assistant "By selecting the foundation and using the end control grips that appear. Drag the grip at either end of the foundation toad just its length. If needed, you can also modify the default end extension length through the type properties."


MESSAGE user "How do I transfer my model to Robot Structural Analysis?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Analyse' ribbon and select 'Robot Structural Analysis Link'. In the integration dialogue box, ensure you're sending the model with direct integration, then click 'OK'. The model will be transferred to Robot, where you can run structural analysis and review results like bending moments and displacements."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a foundation slab?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Structure ribbon, and in the Foundation panel, select 'Structural Foundation Slab'. You can choose between different modes, such as Boundary Line or Slope Arrow, to define the shape of your slab. Once you've selected the mode, trace around your building structure, and then finish by selecting 'Finish Edit Mode' in the context ribbon."


MESSAGE user "What is the difference between a foundation slab and a floor?"
MESSAGE assistant "A foundation slab is similar to a floor but has some key differences. It has additional instance parameters like length and width, while a floor includes parameters like function, variable thickness for layers, and shape editing tools. Shape editing tools are particularly useful for adding drainage points or channels, which is why for some foundation slabs, it’s better to use a floor type."


MESSAGE user "How do I add a slab edge to a foundation slab?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Structure ribbon, under the Foundation panel, and select 'Floor Slab Edge'. You’ll need to load a profile for the slab edge first by selecting the Insert ribbon and clicking 'Load Family'. After that, apply the slab edge to the edge of your slab. You can flip the horizontal or vertical axis of the slab edge if necessary."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a thicker foundation slab?"
MESSAGE assistant "Right-click on your previously placed foundation slab and select 'Repeat Structural Foundation Slab'. Then, change the slab type in the Properties palette to a thicker slab. You can also use the 'Pick Lines' or 'Pick Walls' option to draw the new boundary for the thicker slab."


MESSAGE user "What is the purpose of the slab edge tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "The slab edge tool is used to add chamfers or thickening to the edges of a slab. It allows you to create detailed edges around a slab, including local thickening. This tool doesn't support reinforcement bars or appear in an analytical model, so for structural reinforcement, it's recommended to use a structural beam instead."


MESSAGE user "Can I change the thickness of a slab edge?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, by selecting 'Edit Type' in the Properties palette, duplicating the type, and then adjusting the profile for the slab edge. You can load different profiles for chamfers or thickening to meet your design requirements."


MESSAGE user "How do I edit the length of a slab edge?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the special grips at the start and end of the slab edge. You can click and drag the grips to extend or shorten the edge to fit your desired length, such as aligning it with grid lines."


MESSAGE user "What happens if I need to add a local thickening to a foundation slab?"
MESSAGE assistant "Load the appropriate thickening profile, then use the 'Floor Slab Edge' tool to place the slab edge. Once placed, you can adjust its position and dimensions by modifying the horizontal or vertical profile offsets. This will create a thickened area at a specific location of your slab."


MESSAGE user "How can I view my foundation slab in 3D?"
MESSAGE assistant "Switch to the 3D foundation view in the project browser. You can orbit around the view to see the slabs from different angles. This will allow you to check the placement and thickness of the slabs, as well as any changes made, like chamfers or thickening."


MESSAGE user "What should I do if I want to hide walls temporarily while working on a slab?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can temporarily hide the walls by selecting one of the walls and, in the View Control Toolbar, choose 'Temporary Hide/Isolate' and select 'Hide Category'. This will make it easier to see and work on the slab without the walls obstructing your view."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the profile of a slab edge after placing it?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can change the profile by selecting the slab edge and then going to the Properties palette. Click on 'Edit Type' and select a different profile from the dropdown menu. You can choose profiles for chamfers, thickening, or any other specific shape that suits your design."


