MESSAGE user "How do I create a new project?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the home screen and select 'New Project'. In the New Project dialogue box, make sure you're using the 'Structural Analysis' default template, then click OK. Your new project will be created, defaulting to the Level 2 plan."


MESSAGE user "How do I model a wall?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Structure' ribbon and select 'Wall'. In the Properties palette, ensure that you're using the 'Generic 12 inch' wall type. Then, use the 'Rectangle' tool to draw your walls from Level 2 down to Level 1. After drawing, click 'Modify' to release the wall command."


MESSAGE user "How do I view walls in 3D?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Quick Access Toolbar and select the 'Default 3D View'. If you want to hide the analytical model, go to the View Control Toolbar and click 'Hide Analytical Model'. You can also change the shading to 'Realistic' from the same toolbar for a clearer view of the walls."


MESSAGE user "How do I edit the structure of a wall?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall you want to modify and in the Properties palette, click 'Edit Type'. From the Edit Type dialogue, click 'Edit'. In the Edit Assembly dialogue, you can modify the thickness and structure of the wall. If you want to add a chamfer profile, use the 'Reveals' option in the Assembly dialogue."


MESSAGE user "How do I apply a chamfer profile to a wall?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Edit Assembly' dialogue.  Select 'Reveals' and then 'Load Profile'. Choose the chamfer profile you created earlier, and click 'Apply'. You can set the profile's location by changing the base to 'Top' and selecting the appropriate side of the wall."


MESSAGE user "How do I split a wall with a gap?" 
MESSAGE assistant "To split a wall with a gap, go to the 'Modify' tab, select 'Split with Gap'. Your cursor will change to a knife icon. You can set the gap size in the options bar, and after clicking to place the gap, adjust the dimension using the temporary dimension tool. Once done, click 'Modify' to exit the tool."


MESSAGE user "What happens when I use the 'Split with Gap' tool?" 
MESSAGE assistant "The 'Split with Gap' tool creates a break in the wall with a specified gap between the two segments. This tool is useful for creating thermal expansion joints or gaps between cladding panels. After using the tool, the gap is maintained by a padlock icon, which controls the wall length, while the alignment is maintained by another padlock icon."


MESSAGE user "How do I remove a gap after using the 'Split with Gap' tool?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Unlock the padlock that maintains the length of the gap between the walls. Then, click the 'Allow Join' icon on the walls, and the gap will be removed, making the walls join seamlessly again."


MESSAGE user "How do I connect points using the 'Connect Points' tool?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Autodesk Point Layout tab and select 'Connect Points'. In the Point Selection dialogue, click 'Filter' and choose the desired point description (e.g., 'Existing Underground Utilities'). Then, in the Connection Type dialogue, select 'Pipe' (or another connection type) and specify the pipe size. Click OK to connect the points with your specified connection."


MESSAGE user "How do I use the 'Connect Points' tool for walls?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Select 'Connect Points' again and click 'Filter'. In the Search Filter dialog, choose 'Existing Walls', then click 'Apply'. In the Connection Type dialog, select 'Walls' and specify the level for the wall. The wall will be created and displayed in your drawing at the specified level."


MESSAGE user "How do I modify a connection made with the 'Connect Points' tool?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Select the connected points and adjust the connection type or style as needed. You can also change the level of connection by editing the properties in the dialogue box that appears when selecting the points. To adjust the pipe size or other parameters, revisit the Connection Type and Style dialogues."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a reveal in a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "To create a reveal, go to the Architecture ribbon tab, and from the Build panel, select the Wall Reveal tool. After that, choose the reveal type and click 'Edit Type' to adjust the properties. You can select a specific profile, such as 'Reveal Brick Course One Brick'.  Once done, place the reveal on your wall by clicking where you'd like to position it."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the depth of a reveal in a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the reveal after placing it on the wall. Then, in the Properties palette, change the 'Offset from Wall' parameter. This will move the reveal deeper into the wall, allowing you to control the depth of the recess."


MESSAGE user "How do  I align the reveal with the window above it?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the Align tool from the Modify ribbon tab. Select the underside of the window as the reference plane and then click on the top of the reveal to align it with the window's bottom."


MESSAGE user "How do I copy the reveal to other walls?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the reveal and then click the 'Add/Remove Walls' tool from the Modify Reveals ribbon tab. From there, select the additional walls where you want to place the reveal."


MESSAGE user "How do I copy the reveal to the top of a window?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Modify ribbon tab and select the Copy tool. Choose the bottom of the reveal as the base point and move the cursor to the top of the window to copy it."


MESSAGE user "How can I create a curtain wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "To create a curtain wall, open the floor plan view, then from the Architecture ribbon tab, select the Wall tool. In the Type selector, choose a Curtain Wall type, such as 'Curtain Wall – Glazing'. Draw the curtain wall by clicking the start and end points of the wall. Ensure that you set the correct height in the Options bar."


MESSAGE user "How do I divide a curtain wall into smaller panels?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the curtain wall and click 'Edit Type' from the Properties palette. In the Type Properties dialogue, change the vertical and horizontal grid layout to 'Fixed Distance' and set the spacing for each grid line. After applying the changes, the curtain wall will be divided into smaller panels based on the grid spacing."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the justification of the curtain wall grid?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Type Properties dialogue of the curtain wall. In the vertical grid panel, look for the 'Justification' parameter. You can choose from 'Begin', 'End', or 'Centre' to adjust how the grid lines are distributed across the curtain wall."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the profile of a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and click 'Edit Profile' from the Modify Walls ribbon tab. In the sketch mode, you can adjust the shape of the wall by drawing lines or picking reference points. Once you're satisfied, click 'Finish Edit Mode' to apply the changes."


MESSAGE user "How do I offset a wall profile along a ramp?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and click 'Edit Profile' from the Modify Walls ribbon tab. In sketch mode, use the 'Pick Lines' tool and set the offset value in the options bar. Then, click along the ramp to define the new profile, and use the 'Trim Extend to Corner' tool to tidy up the sketch."


MESSAGE user "How do I draw a wall profile to follow stairs?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and click 'Edit Profile' from the Modify Walls ribbon tab. In sketch mode, use the 'Pick Lines' tool to define the slope along the stairs. Set the offset if needed, and then use the 'Trim Extend to Corner' tool to clean up the profile. Click 'Finish Edit Mode' to finalise the shape."


MESSAGE user "How do I swap walls for a new wall type?"
MESSAGE assistant "Start by selecting one of the walls that hasn't been changed yet. Right-click and choose 'Select All Instances'.  Next, choose 'Entire Project' to select all the walls in the project. Then, go to the Properties Palette, click the Type Selector, and choose the new wall type. This will change all selected walls to the new type."


MESSAGE user "How do I make a wall slanted?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall you want to change, and then go to the Properties Palette. In the Cross Section Definition panel, change the Cross Section from 'Vertical' to 'Slanted'.  Below that, adjust the 'Angle from Vertical' to your desired degree (e.g., 10 degrees). You can tweak this angle until you achieve the slant you want."


MESSAGE user "How can I attach a wall to a floor?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the floor and then click 'Edit Boundary' from the Modify Floors ribbon. After editing, click 'Finish Edit Mode', and it will ask if you want to attach the walls to the floor. Click 'Attach'.  Now the walls will follow any changes you make to the floor, such as elevation adjustments."


MESSAGE user "How do I attach walls to a roof?"
MESSAGE assistant "Create or select your roof and then select the walls you want to attach and go to the Modify Walls ribbon. Click 'Attach Top/Base' and choose 'Top'.  Finally, select the roof, and the walls will be attached to its underside. Any changes made to the roof will now affect the attached walls."


MESSAGE user "How do I place a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Architecture ribbon, and in the Build panel, click 'Wall: Architecture'.  Then, in the Type Selector, choose the wall type you want to place. Next, select your drawing method (e.g., Line) and click in the drawing area to start the wall. As you move the cursor, a temporary dimension will appear to guide the wall placement. Click to place the wall, or type a dimension value and press ENTER."


MESSAGE user "How do I modify wall properties after placement?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can modify its properties anytime by selecting the wall and then adjusting its settings in the Properties palette. You can change parameters like Location Line, Base Constraint, Top Constraint, and other properties such as material or thickness."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the detail level of a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the View Control Bar at the bottom of your screen. Click on the Detail Level dropdown and select either 'Coarse', 'Medium', or 'Fine' to adjust how detailed the wall layers are displayed in your view."


MESSAGE user "How do I modify the cross-section of a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and open the Properties Palette. In the 'Cross Section' section, change the setting from 'Vertical' to 'Slanted'.  Then, adjust the 'Angle from Vertical' to the desired angle to slant the wall in your model."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a roof by footprint?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Architecture ribbon and click 'Roof by Footprint' in the Build panel. Then, choose the sketching tool (such as Circle) to define the roof’s shape. After that, draw the roof and use slope arrows to define the pitch. Finish by clicking 'Finish Edit Mode' to create the roof."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the height of a roof?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the roof in your project, then go to the Properties Palette. Adjust the 'Base Offset from Level' or change the 'Height Offset' to increase or decrease the roof's elevation. You can also edit the roof’s footprint and adjust the slope if needed."


MESSAGE user "How do I align walls?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Modify tab and select the Align tool. You will need to pick the reference, which will not move, and then select the element you want to align. After that, you can lock the alignment if you want it to stay fixed, or just leave it without the constraint. If you need to align multiple walls, enable the 'Multiple Alignment' option in the options bar and select the walls to align them to the reference wall."


MESSAGE user "What is the purpose of locking the alignment constraint?"
MESSAGE assistant "Locking the alignment constraint ensures that the elements stay aligned even if other elements are moved. Once locked, if you drag one wall, the other wall will move with it, maintaining the alignment. This is useful when you want to ensure that two elements remain in the same relative position."


MESSAGE user "Can I align multiple walls at once?"
MESSAGE assistant "Yes, you can. After selecting the Align tool, enable the 'Multiple Alignment' option in the options bar. Then, select the reference wall, and click on each wall you want to align to it. All selected walls will move into alignment with the reference wall, and you can choose whether to lock the alignment constraint for each one."


MESSAGE user "How do I undo an alignment change?"
MESSAGE assistant "Click the 'Undo' button on the Quick Access Toolbar. This will revert the last action and move the wall back to its original position before the alignment was made."


MESSAGE user "What happens if I don't lock the alignment constraint?"
MESSAGE assistant "The walls will align but won’t be forced to stay together if you move one. They will not maintain their relative position unless you manually realign them later."


MESSAGE user "How can I change the reference for alignment?"
MESSAGE assistant "Click on the current reference in the options bar and choose a new reference. For example, you can switch from aligning to the wall face to aligning to the centreline of the wall, depending on your requirements."


MESSAGE user "How do I mark wall points?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Autodesk Point Layout tab, APL panel, and click 'Wall Points'.  In the Add Points dialogue, choose the point start number, prefix, role, and phase. You can also select the type name to use the wall type for the description or opt for custom descriptions. Choose whether to mark the top, bottom, or both of the walls, and then click OK to add the points to your drawing."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a wall layout?"
MESSAGE assistant "To create a simple wall layout, click on 'Wall' in the Build panel on the ribbon. Set the wall’s location line, height, and type, and then start drawing the walls by clicking to place them. You can enter specific distances or snap to other walls using the alignment tool. If you want to exit the wall tool, press 'Escape' twice."


MESSAGE user "How do I align twowalls?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the first wall, click and drag it. As you move it, alignment lines will appear, showing when the walls are aligned. Oncethey align, a padlock icon will appear, allowing you to lock the alignment, ensuring that both walls move together. To unlock the alignment, click the padlock icon."


MESSAGE user "How do I draw a curved wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select 'Create Similar' from the right-click menu or the ribbon to match the properties of an existing wall. Choose the 'Start-End-Radius' tool in the Draw panel. Click to define the starting and ending points,and move the cursor to create a curved wall. Once the radius is set, click to finish drawing the curve."


MESSAGE user "What are the priority clean-up numbers for walls?"
MESSAGE assistant "The priority clean-up numbers are used to define which wall layers take precedence when two layers overlap. The number 1 is the highest priority, while number 5 is the lowest. When two walls with the same material overlap, they will blend, but if they have different materials, a dividing line will appear. If a higher-priority layer crosses over a lower-priority one, it will clean up and cut through the lower layer."


MESSAGE user "How can I review the points after marking them?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can review them in the 3D view by opening the Default 3D View from the Quick Access Toolbar. You’ll see the points placed at key locations, such as intersections, tops, bottoms, and openings. You can select any point to view its properties and make any necessary changes."


MESSAGE user "How doI modify the wall type?" 
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and go to the Properties palette. Click on 'Edit Type' to open the Type Properties dialogue box. Here, you can adjust the dimensions, materials, and other properties of the wall type."


MESSAGE user "How do I zoom into a specific region in the building?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the navigation bar and choose the 'Zoom Region' tool. Draw a box around the area you want to zoom into, and it will focus on that section of the building."


MESSAGE user "How do I fix wall junctions that are not properly joined?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Modify ribbon tab, select the Geometry panel, and click 'Wall Joins'.  Then, select the wall junction you want to edit. You can cycle through different junction options by clicking 'Next' until you get the desired configuration."


MESSAGE user "How do I modify sharp corners in wall junctions?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the Wall Joins tool from the Modify ribbon tab. Select the sharp corner you want to adjust, and click 'Next' to cycle through different junction types. You can choose 'Square off' to reduce a 90-degree angle for a more realistic and less vulnerable junction."


MESSAGE user "How do I duplicate and edit a wall type?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select an existing wall in the model and go to the Type Selector in the properties palette, click 'Edit Type'.  In the Type Properties window, click 'Duplicate', assign a new name for the wall, and click 'OK' to create the new wall type. After that, you can adjust the wall's assembly and other settings as needed."


MESSAGE user "How do I add insulation layers to a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Type Properties for the wall and click 'Edit'. In the 'Edit Assembly' window, use the 'Insert' button to add a new layer. You can set the thickness of the insulation layer and assign the material to the new layer."


MESSAGE user "How do I apply materials to different wall layers?"
MESSAGE assistant "Open the 'Edit Assembly' window for the wall. Click on the 'By Category' material for each layer and launch the Material Browser by clicking the ellipsis button.Search for the desired material (e.g., insulation, plywood), select it, and click 'OK' to assign it to the layer. Repeat this for each layer."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign functions to wall layers?"
MESSAGE assistant "In the 'Edit Assembly' window, go to the 'Function' column for each layer. Choose a function from the drop-down list (such as 'Structure', 'Finish', or 'Thermal Layer') depending on the role of that layer. For example, assign 'Finish' for insulation layers and 'Structure' for core layers."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the wall material in the 3D view?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall you want to edit and go to the Type Properties, click 'Edit Type'.  From there, you can rename the wall type and then edit the assembly by changing the material in the 'Structure' section. Use the Material Browser to choose a new material for the wall layers."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a brick soldier course within a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and go to 'Edit Type'.  Open the 'Edit Assembly' window and use the 'Split Region' tool to add split lines where the soldier course will go. Set the dimensions for the soldier course, then add a new layer at the top of the wall and assign the brick material to it. Finally, use the 'Assign Layers' tool to apply the brick material to the soldier course region."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the display detail level of a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the View Control Bar at the bottom of the view and select 'Medium' or 'Fine' from the 'Detail Level' options. This will update the view and display the wall layers more clearly, including any modifications like the brick soldier course."


MESSAGE user "How do I apply changes to multiple instances of a wall type?"
MESSAGE assistant "Right-click on one of the walls and select 'Select All Instances Visible in View.' Then, in the Type Selector, choose the newly created wall type, and the changes will be applied to all selected instances."


MESSAGE user "How do I manipulate the preview window when editing a wall assembly?"
MESSAGE assistant "Change the sample height to your desired value (e.g., 10 ft or 15 ft) using the top-right corner of the 'Edit Assembly' window."


MESSAGE user "How do I change the top offset of a wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall, then go to the Properties palette and in the Constraints panel, find the 'Top Offset' parameter and adjust it to your desired value."


MESSAGE user "How can I embed one wall into another?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall you want to cut and go to the Modify tab. Use the 'Cap Geometry' tool to embed the wall into the host wall."


MESSAGE user "How do I copy windows to the clipboard?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the Modify tab, and click on the 'Copy to Clipboard' button in the Clipboard panel."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new brick wall embedded into an existing stone wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the floor plan view, select the Wall tool, choose the exterior brick on CMU wall type, and draw the wall between the reference planes. Then, use the 'Cap Geometry' tool to embed the brick wall into the stone wall."


MESSAGE user "How do I adjust the height of a brick panel wall to match an existing one?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the wall and go to the Properties palette. Find the 'Top Constraint' parameter and change it to 'Up to Level Roof'.  This will adjust the height to match the existing wall."


MESSAGE user "How do I use the 'Join Geometry' tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select 'Join Geometry' from the Geometry panel, and click on the walls you want to join together. This will eliminate any joint lines between the walls."


MESSAGE user "How can I create a fillet between two adjacent walls?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the Wall tool and create a similar wall using the 'Create Similar' tool. Then, select the 'Fillet Arc' tool from the Draw panel, click on the first wall, and then the second wall to create the arc."


MESSAGE user "How do I trim or extend walls to a corner?"
MESSAGE assistant "Use the 'Trim/Extend to Corner' tool found in the Modify tab and click on the two walls that will form the corner, and the tool will trim or extend the walls to meet at the corner."


MESSAGE user "How do I extend a single wall to another wall?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the 'Trim/Extend Single Elements' tool from the Modify tab. Click on the reference wall, select the wall you want to extend, and it will be extended to the reference wall."


MESSAGE user "How do I trim and extend multiple walls simultaneously?"
MESSAGE assistant "Select the 'Trim/Extend Multiple Elements' tool from the Modify tab. Click on the reference element and use a crossing window to select the walls you want to trim and extend. Release the mouse to apply the changes."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a retaining wall with a sloped face?"
MESSAGE assistant "You can use a wall and sweep to create the sloped face. Start by creating a profile with the appropriate angle and wall height, then apply the formula to calculate the thickness of the base based on the angle and height. Use the standard wall foundation tool for the foundation, and you can adjust the profile to fit deeper wall depths if necessary."


MESSAGE user "How do I use a formula within parameters for calculations?"
MESSAGE assistant "To calculate the thickness of a retaining wall’s base, you would use the tangent of the face angle and multiply it by the wall height. First, create parameters for the angle, wall height, and profile width. Then, input a formula for the profile width to calculate it dynamically based on the angle and height values you enter."


MESSAGE user "How do I create a new family?"
MESSAGE assistant "Opening the home screen and select 'New Family'. In the 'New Family' dialogue box, choose 'Profile.rft' and click 'Open'. This will open the family editor, where you can create and define your custom profile using reference planes and dimensions."


MESSAGE user "How do I assign parameters to a family?"
MESSAGE assistant "After creating reference planes  go to the 'Family Types' dialogue box to create new parameters, such as 'Face Angle' and 'Wall Height'. Then, assign these parameters to the appropriate dimensions and reference planes in your profile to drive the geometry based on the values you input."


MESSAGE user "How do I test a family after creating it?"
MESSAGE assistant "Open the 'Family Types' dialogue box and alter the values for factors like 'Face Angle' or 'Wall Height'. Check the geometry to determine whether the changes update appropriately depending on the parameter values once they have been applied. This ensures  that your formulas and settings are operating as they should."


MESSAGE user "What is the Split Element tool used for?"
MESSAGE assistant "The Split Element tool is used to divide an element, like a wall, into multiple segments. You can use it to split walls into smaller sections for purposes like changing wall types, deleting parts of the wall, or replacing segments with different elements. Once you split an element, you can adjust the dimensions or replace the split sections as needed."


MESSAGE user "How do I split a wall using the Split Element tool?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Modify' tab and choose 'Split Element' to divide a wall. Click at the wall you wish to split it at. There will be two sections to the wall, each which you can move or change separately. Changing the temporary dimensions helps you to change the split's position."


MESSAGE user "How do use the Align tool to align elements?"
MESSAGE assistant "Go to the 'Modify' tab to utilise the Align tool; choose 'Align' from the Modify panel. Then you will be asked to choose the elements you wish to line up. You can select the alignment technique that of aligning to the centres of the elements, faces, or centre lines by means of the options bar. After selecting your reference and target elements, click to align them."


MESSAGE user "What do the different alignment options in the Align tool mean?"
MESSAGE assistant "The alignment options in the Align tool include 'Centre Lines' (which aligns the middle of two elements), 'All Faces' (aligns the exterior or interior faces of elements), 'Centre of Core' (aligns the corecentres), and 'Faces of Core' (aligns specific layers of the core, such as the internal or external core). These options are useful depending on the type of elements you're aligning and the desired result."